@startuml recall-internal-bounding
' What keeps the Recall tier SMALL so brute-force stays cheap -- from RECALL's
' OWN point of view (the full consolidation mechanics are the tandem diagrams).
' Two bounding forces, both enqueue a CONSOLIDATE (the outflow):
'   (1) per-(tenant,dataset) cap RB_RECALL_MAX_ROWS -- after a write/delete, if
'       recall_partition_count(...) > cap, enqueue CONSOLIDATE (best-effort,
'       after the durable write).
'   (2) idle window RB_RECALL_IDLE_S -- the builder idle-tick sweep
'       (recall_idle_partitions) enqueues CONSOLIDATE for any partition whose
'       newest write is older than the window -> drained to ZERO rows ->
'       idle queries skip pgvector (scale-to-zero).
' CONSOLIDATE is drawn only as the OUTFLOW; its internals are out of scope.
'
' Layout: a clean top->bottom pipeline. recall_vectors GROWS at the top; the two
' triggers sit in the middle and both feed CONSOLIDATE at the bottom; the single
' drain back-edge (right side) closes the loop. Few edges, short labels.

title Recall internals: what keeps the set small (cap + idle drain)

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowFontSize 11
skinparam NoteFontSize 10
skinparam wrapWidth 230
skinparam nodesep 45
skinparam ranksep 55

database "recall_vectors\n(rows + tombstones grow on\nevery sync write / delete)" as rv #F4F8FF

card "(1) CAP trigger -- on write/delete\nrecall_partition_count(t,d)\n> RB_RECALL_MAX_ROWS (2000)?" as cap #LightYellow
card "(2) IDLE trigger -- builder idle tick\nmax(created_at) older than\nRB_RECALL_IDLE_S (60s)?\n(recall_idle_partitions)" as idle #LightYellow

queue "CONSOLIDATE\n(the OUTFLOW -- builder folds the partition\ninto a shard; mechanics out of scope here)" as q

' down: grow -> trigger checks -> enqueue
rv --> cap : on write / delete
rv --> idle : on idle tick
cap --> q : > cap -> enqueue\n(best-effort, after\ndurable write)
idle --> q : idle -> enqueue\nper partition

' single back-edge closes the loop (drain)
q -[#0a7]-> rv : drain -> rows trimmed\n(idle drains to ZERO)

note left of cap #E9F7E9
  Bounds the brute-force scan size and
  stops one chatty tenant evicting
  another's working set. Best-effort
  AFTER the committed write -> a cap-check
  failure never fails the write.
end note

note right of idle #E7F3FD
  Drains an idle partition to ZERO recall
  rows -> idle queries skip pgvector
  entirely (scale-to-zero preserved).
end note

note bottom of q #FDF3E7
  Recall is bounded by CONSOLIDATION CADENCE, not data
  size. Bulk imports BYPASS recall (land straight to the
  consolidated tier), so a large dump never enters here.
  => the set stays small => exact L2 stays cheap.
end note

@enduml
